@node release "RELEASE 2.5"
Version 2.5 adds most relevant "CD2" features and a couple of things from CD3.  I have not bumped
the version number to 3.x as the most important parts - download of 03p data,
and uploads/downloads of audio data - are not implemented at all.  In addition I have not
tested the additions between 2.4 and 2.5.


I have now discontinued development of Ambot.  It was an interesting project but due to time
constraints I am not able to progress it as far as I would like it to be.  In particular, the GUI
needs revamping - especially that of "Blocks" needs an overhaul - and the protocol/format for
download and upload of audio and blocks data needs decyphering.


As such, this final release contains the original C source code, the use of which has
few limitations.  You can hack it around, use code in your own projects and basically
do what you like with it providing I am credited for any of my code that is used.
The code is restricted for non-commercial non-military use only.  If you want to use it
for commercial purposes, contact me and we can come to an agreement.  If you want to use
it to harm people, destroy cities or even scare little bunny wabbits, this is explicitly
disallowed.


If you update Ambot please also release the updated source code.

@endnode

@node connecting "Connecting"
Connect the handset to the Amiga by way of the cable supplied with Issue 37 and a
serial port adapter (25-pin to 9-pin - these are plentiful and easily obtainable)
If you do not connect it to the internal serial port, you will need to change the
@{"tooltypes" link tooltypes} for DEVICE and UNIT.  Connect it with the Amiga
turned off or you risk potentially expensive damage.


Switch Cybot on and ensure it is set to Channel 01 ("1" should be flashing on the
rear LCD display).  The DIP switches should all be set to the UP position (change
them with the robot switched OFF if they are not)


Ambot requires OS3.5 or up to function as it uses the Reaction classes.

@endnode

@node simple "Programmer01"
The "simple" tab on the GUI is an implementation of Programmer01 as found on CD1.  It is not as graphically pretty but performs the same function.  Select the action Cybot should take from the cycle gadgets, next to the the text explaining where the hazard is detected.  The options should be fairly self-explanatory and directly map to the corresponding arrows on the official programmer.


Note that the non-selectable "Advanced" option signifies that the option has been fine-tuned in the advanced mode.  You can switch between simple and advanced at the drop of a hat - something you can't do easily with the official programmer.

@endnode

@node advanced "Programmer02"
The "advanced" tab on the GUI is an implementation of Programmer02 on CD1.  The interface is not the same as the original, but performs the same function.  This has changed since v1.3.


The gadgets are in pairs, with the left numerical gadget indicating the speed of the left motor, and the right gadget indicating the speed of the right motor.  Further to the right means the hazard detected on the right is further away, lower down the table means the left hazard is further away - it is a 135° rotation of the original design.  Note that the gadgets don't quite line up, I'm working on fixing this.  Ideally it should look like this:

@{code}
Left side   | Right side hazard distance
hazard dist | Very close | 10cm away  | 20cm away  |None detected
------------+------------+------------+------------+--------------
Very close  |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]
------------+------------+------------+------------+--------------
10cm away   |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]
------------+------------+------------+------------+--------------
20cm away   |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]
------------+------------+------------+------------+--------------
None detect |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]  |  [L]  [R]
@{body}


The above should help you work out the gadgets on the GUI until I get the layout properly fixed.

@endnode

@node blocks "Programmer03"
interface changing regulary so no documentation yet

@endnode

@node open "Open File"
This option provides an ASL file requester from which you can select files saved both
by the official Windows Cybot Programmer (CD1 supplied with Issue 38), and
Ambot.  Note that .ROB files are saved by Programmer01 and .RDR are saved by Programmer02.
Unfortunately there is no easy way to determine the file format other than by filename.
If there is no file extension, Ambot will try to load the file in the native format of the current
tab, if it is not in that format, the behaviour of Ambot is undefined. 

@endnode

@node save "Save File"
Selecting "Save" will provide an ASL file requester to enter a filename and path to save
the program to.  You should specify a file extension as Ambot uses this to determine the
format you want to save in!  If you do not, Ambot will assume the native format of the
current tab.


It is recommended to save files in .RDR format as this contains more information.
.RDR and .ROB files are interchangeable between Ambot and the official programmers.
However, if the simple programmer shows "Advanced" for any options, .ROB will not
contain enough information to recreate the program, and the behaviour of both Ambot
and the official programmer is undefined if you attempt to reload such a program.


Blocks programs need to be saved in .03P format.

@endnode


@node download "Transfer programs to Cybot"
Ambot has an option not found in the official Programmer: you can download both
Programmer01 (.RDR) and Programmer02 (.ROB) programs to program areas 01 and 02.  In
addition it seems to be much faster at downloading.


Ensure the correct program to download is in memory.  Select the download option and choose the program number.  You will then be prompted to ensure everything is set
up correctly.  This will only appear once per session - next time ensure everything is set up and ready to go before clicking Download.


Make sure:

1. The handset is connected

2. Cybot is switched on and on channel 01

3. The handset is pointing towards Cybot's infrared sensor

4. The handset is in PC LINK mode and the progress bar is showing

   (option 4, best to select it just before clicking OK on the requester)


Ambot will tell you where the communication failure occured.  In my experience, most problems are a result of #3.  I have had limited success with
downloading, and although Cybot will happily respond to the handset no matter where you
point it, when downloading it is significantly more fussy.  Mostly this may be due to a bug in v1.2 which made the transfer very unreliable, but even with the PC I have occasional problems.  Experience tells me that it may be battery-related - the handset eats batteries, and from my limited attempts, high-power rechargeable batteries (WARNING: it does tell you not to use rechargeable batteries, so if you want to try them you do so AT YOUR OWN RISK) only work reliably when @{i}they have drained down somewhat@{ui}.  Even the best alkaline batteries money can buy only work for a limited number of transfer attempts.


Hold it steady, hold it close and try again if you don't get a "Download Complete" message.

@endnode

